  <div style="font-size:.8rem;color:var(--ink3);margin-bottom:24px;padding:12px 16px;background:var(--surface);border-radius:8px;">
    Data sourced from WHO Global Health Observatory, NCD Risk Factor Collaboration (NCD-RisC), and national health surveys. Values represent population averages for adults 18+, typically from 2016–2024 data cycles. Obesity rate defined as BMI ≥30.
  </div>

  <div class="article-section">
    <h2>Global BMI Trends: What the Data Shows</h2>
    <p>Global average BMI has increased dramatically over the past 50 years. The NCD Risk Factor Collaboration, which pooled data from 200 countries and 128 million people, found:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Global average BMI rose from <strong>~21.7 in 1975 to ~26.5 in 2024</strong> for both men and women</li>
      <li>The number of obese adults worldwide increased from 100 million in 1975 to over <strong>890 million in 2022</strong></li>
      <li>Obesity rates have more than <strong>doubled in most countries</strong> since 1980</li>
      <li>Low and middle-income countries are experiencing the fastest rate of increase</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Countries With the Highest Average BMI</h2>
    <p>Pacific Island nations dominate the upper end of global BMI rankings. Nauru has the world's highest recorded average BMI at approximately 34–36 for adults, with obesity rates above 70%. This reflects a complex combination of factors including rapid dietary transition from traditional foods to imported processed foods, genetic predisposition, and limited physical activity infrastructure.</p>
    <p>Among larger nations, the United States has one of the highest average BMIs in the developed world at approximately 29.5 for men and 29.6 for women — placing the average American just below the obese threshold. Egypt has one of the highest average BMIs in Africa, with women averaging approximately 31.8.</p>

    <h2>Countries With the Lowest Average BMI</h2>
    <p>East and Southeast Asian nations, along with several sub-Saharan African countries, have the world's lowest average BMIs. Japan's average BMI of approximately 23.6 for men and 22.3 for women is particularly notable given Japan's status as a high-income nation — it reflects culturally embedded dietary habits (fish, vegetables, smaller portions) and social norms around body weight.</p>
    <p>Vietnam and Bangladesh also have very low average BMIs (approximately 21), though this partly reflects food insecurity rather than optimal health.</p>
    <div class="callout"><p>💡 Important note: low BMI is not always healthy. In low-income countries, a low average BMI often reflects undernutrition rather than optimal weight. The healthiest populations have average BMIs in the 22–25 range.</p></div>

    <h2>Why Asian BMI Thresholds Are Different</h2>
    <p>Standard WHO BMI categories (overweight ≥25, obese ≥30) were developed primarily from European population data. Research has consistently shown that adults of Asian descent develop metabolic health risks — type 2 diabetes, cardiovascular disease, hypertension — at lower BMI values than European populations.</p>
    <p>The WHO issued a recommendation that for Asian populations, a BMI of ≥23 should be considered overweight and ≥27.5 should be considered obese. Despite having lower average BMIs than Western countries, many Asian nations have significant rates of metabolic disease.</p>
    <p>Use our <a href="asian-bmi-calculator.html">Asian BMI Calculator</a> if you are of Asian descent to get a more appropriate BMI assessment.</p>

