  </div>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2 class="section-title">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Which country has the highest average BMI?</button>
      <div class="faq-a">Pacific Island nations consistently have the highest average BMIs. Nauru, Cook Islands, Palau, Marshall Islands, and Tonga all have average BMIs above 30. Among larger nations, the United States, Mexico, and several Gulf states also have very high average BMIs.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Which country has the lowest average BMI?</button>
      <div class="faq-a">East and Southeast Asian nations tend to have the lowest average BMIs among reasonably nourished populations. Japan and Vietnam have average BMIs around 22–23. Ethiopia and Bangladesh have very low average BMIs, but this partly reflects food insecurity.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the average BMI in the United States?</button>
      <div class="faq-a">The average BMI in the United States is approximately 29.0–29.5 for adults, placing the average American in the overweight category. Approximately 42% of US adults are obese (BMI 30 or above) and a further 31% are overweight.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">What is the average BMI in the UK?</button>
      <div class="faq-a">The average BMI in the UK is approximately 27.5 for adults. Around 28% of English adults are obese and a further 38% are overweight, meaning over two-thirds of UK adults have a BMI above the healthy range.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">Why do Asian countries have lower average BMIs?</button>
      <div class="faq-a">East and Southeast Asian populations tend to have lower average BMIs due to a combination of genetic factors, traditional dietary patterns, and cultural attitudes. However, the health risk thresholds are also lower — the WHO recommends a lower overweight threshold of BMI 23 for Asian adults, as they develop metabolic disease at lower BMI values.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

